/*
Problem: Greatest Common Divisor (GCD)

Given two positive integers n1 and n2, return their Greatest Common Divisor (GCD).

Approach (Brute Force):
1. The GCD cannot be greater than the smaller of the two numbers.
2. Iterate from 1 to min(n1, n2).
3. If a number divides both n1 and n2, update the GCD.
4. The last common divisor found is the Greatest Common Divisor.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int GCD(int n1, int n2) {
        int gc = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i <= min(n1, n2); i++) {
            if (n1 % i == 0 && n2 % i == 0) {
                gc = i;
            }
        }

        return gc;
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity: O(min(n1, n2))
Space Complexity: O(1)

Mistakes I Made:
1. Initially checked only:
      n2 % i == 0
   This verified divisibility for only one number.
   For GCD, 'i' must divide both numbers.

2. Initially iterated till n1.
   Optimized it to iterate till min(n1, n2) because
   the GCD can never be greater than the smaller number.

3. This is the brute-force approach.
   The optimal solution uses Euclid's Algorithm,
   which has a time complexity of O(log(min(n1, n2))).
*/
